<TITLE> Desperate dash for home </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Mohsinul Karim bdnews24.com correspondent Dhaka, Dec 8 (bdnews24.com)  People in their thousands streamed to the bus, railway and launch terminals in the capital in a desperate dash for home to celebrate Eid-ul-Azha on Tuesday. They defied traffic jam, high fares and ticket crisis, bdnews24.com correspondent Mohsinul Karim, who was headed for Nilphamari from Dhaka on Sunday night, reported. Tickets were sold more than the number of seats and many risked their lives by traveling on the roofs, exposing themselves to cold wintry night. There was mad rush in Nabil Paribahan counter at Shyamoli and the company officials sold more tickets than the number of seats they could offer. Ticket-seller Sweet, who gave only one name, said they had not intended to sell additional tickets. "Many people would not be able to go homes if we did not do that. We were compelled to sell the additional tickets due to the pressure of the passengers and on humanitarian ground," he said. The bus started at 10pm from Gabtoli which suffered huge traffic congestion due to a cattle market there. The driver took Ashulia route to avoid the trouble and reach early, but to no avail. The bus could not cross Ashulia before 11pm. There were 40 seats in Nabil Paribahan bus, but 53 passengers. Eight people were seated on engine and the remaining ones stood. Some simply climbed onto the roof without caring to buy tickets. A looking out of the window and there one could see that most buses had passengers on their roofs. The bus operators raised the fares, as usual. They charged Tk 480 against Tk 340 on Dhaka-Dimla route for each passenger, seated or standing. b
